description: The Captain is a two-day mountain biking enduro.  Each segment includes untimed climbing and individually timed decents.  Shuttle service provided for both a.m. races.
course:
Saturday-a.m. Pipeline to 7-Bridges trails ~6 miles, p.m. multiple courses decending at Palmer Park.
Sunday-a.m. St. Marys trail ~6 miles
notes: Three individually timed races spanning Saturday and Sunday.  Long segments are between 6 and 8 miles in length each of primarily decending on rugged single track.  Short segments consist of four different tracks ranging in expected finishing times of 3-8 minutes.  These short segments are also individually timed with untimed climbs connecting starts and finishes.

title: 27th Annual Longmont Criterium
description: 27th Annual Longmont Criterium. Colorado Senior State Championship
course: The .7 mile "L" shaped course is mostly flat and winds around historic Thompson Park. Wide, smooth streets make this an amazing event for both racers and spectators. The start/finish area and registration is located near the intersection of Pratt & 4th.
registration: Preregistration is available at usacycling.org until 11:30 p.m. July 12, 2013. $35 prereg/$40 race day. Fee for second race is $15. Race will run regardless of weather conditions. Race day registration opens at 6:45 a.m. and closes 40 minutes prior to each race. Registration includes all processing fees.
directions:
Denver: 1-25 north to CO 119 exit. Take 119 west to 3rd Ave. Turn right/north on 3rd Ave. Continue one block west of Main Street. Turn right/north on Coffman St. 
Ft Collin: 1-25 south to CO 119 exit. Take 119 west to 3rd Ave. Turn right/north on 3rd Ave. Continue one block west of Main Street. Turn right/north on Coffman St. 
Boulder: Diagonal Hwy/119 north to Hover Rd. Turn north on Hover to 3rd Ave. Turn right/east on 3rd Ave. Turn left on Coffman St. 
Parking: Parking is available at the Longmont Times-Call parking lot at the corner of 4th and Terry (one block west of Coffman St). Additional parking is available on city streets and public lots but obey all parking laws and be respectful of local residents and businesses.

title: Steamboat Stinger
description:
2013 is here and so is the 3rd annual Steamboat Stinger! This time with a bigger field and another day of added fun and suffering! The Steamboat Stinger aims to provide a challenging backcountry race experience showcasing some of Steamboat Springs\' finest singletrack. 

Once again, we will feature a full and half trail marathon in addition to our Mountain Bike Race. These two events can be separate, or if you wish to take the ultimate challenge, you can participate in both events - the 50 mile solo mountain bike race, and then the 26.2 trail marathon the next day - to be crowned King Sting or Queen Bee of the Steamboat Stinger.

These events are true to Steamboat Springs\' tradition: epic fun with the added bit of western flair. Giddy up!
course: You can expect singletrack…lots of it. Beginning at the Howelson Hill Ski Area right in the heart of Steamboat, the course takes an extended detour deep into the beautiful backcountry of Routt County before returning to the transition/finish area. Racers will wind through open meadows, deeply-cupped, aspen-lined, narrow Colorado loam and wild sage gardens offering incredible views of the surrounding peaks and valleys. It\'s a 50-mile race composed of two 25-mile loops - 100% of which are on dirt featuring 90% singletrack.
registration:
Registration opens March 1st, all through Prerace.com

No day of Registration
notes: This is the third year, Last years winners were Russell Finsterwald in Pro/Open Men and Katie Compton in Pro/Open Women
directions: Once entering town, look to the left, at the base of the Howelsen Hill Ski jumps is the start/Finish of the race.

title: AADA Monarch Crest Crank
description: Noncompetitive mountain bike ride fundraiser for the Alliance Against Domestic Abuse
course: Intermediate to advanced trail spanning approximately 20-34 miles along the famed Monarch Crest trail along the Continental Divide, and continuing on to descend the Rainbow Trail, or riders may choose to descend Marshall Pass road at the point of divide.
notes: Starting on the ridge of the Continental Divide at the 11,312ft Monarch Pass and climbing up from there, the 20-34 mile ride depending on choice of route to descend.  Consists primarily of singletrack that keeps riders above 11,000ft for approximately 11 miles before gradually dropping to 7,000ft.
directions: Salida Colorado 148 North F Street, shuttle to take riders to top of Monarch Pass

title: USA Cycling Bill Woodul Race Mechanics Clinic
Gunny Cross
description: Gunnison cyclocross will be the regional championship for the RMCCC cyclocross season. The race will determine the call up for the National championship in Boulder 2014. The race will be held 12:00- 2:00 on the western state campus (600 Nth Adams St. Gunnison CO 81231).  The course will be technical and hilly around the Western State Colorado University campus.
course: The course will include barriers, stairs, sandpits and other technical features. The course will be around 3/4 of a mile long and weave through campus. The course will climb  a lot around campus and have some open straight away to let lose. Campus will still be open so watch out for student and citizens walking around and spectating.
registration: Registration will be held Sun 9am-11am at the University Center. Registration will be $30 for the regional championship race.
directions: The course will be on campus at 600 Nth Adams St. Gunnison CO 81230. The start finish registration area will be in the University Center. To get there by car follow Esclante drive to the north end of campus there will be a large parking lot opposite of the football field. We will stage the race on the south side of the UIniversty Center.
